{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502751"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1897"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1897"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.12,0.04,0.24,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1897"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83005"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1897"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1897"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68065"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"949"},{"type":"tags","id":"1097"},{"type":"tags","id":"6292"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39839"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83005"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old man presents to a new General Practice clinic for a general check-up. The General Practitioner notices a deformity in the patient\u0027s arm, but the patient is unable to provide any explanation except that he injured his arm when he was young and it has been like this ever since. He is unable to move the wrist or fingers from the position seen in the image. The General Practitioner additionally notes marked atrophy of the forearm on the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is otherwise well with no significant medical history, and the General Practitioner finds no other deformities on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following injuries would most plausibly cause the above deformity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Penetrating injury to the hand","Disruption of the metacarpophalangeal joints","Dislocation of the carpal bones","Fracture of the distal radius","Fracture of the distal humerus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of a Volkmann\u0027s ischaemic contracture. This is the result of an acute ischaemic insult to the flexor muscles of the forearm causing permanent fibrosis and shortening. The most common cause is a \u003Cstrong\u003Efracture of the distal humerus\u003C/strong\u003E - specifically a displaced supracondylar fracture causing either disruption of the brachial artery, or compartment syndrome of the forearm. This is a rare condition which can be treated with physical therapy and surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPenetrating injury to the hand\u003C/strong\u003E would not typically cause this deformity, and in particular would not cause the associated forearm atrophy and fixed wrist flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of the metacarpophalangeal joints\u003C/strong\u003E would likewise not account for the forearm and wrist findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDislocation of the carpal bones\u003C/strong\u003E does not typically cause fixed deformities of the fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFracture of the distal radius\u003C/strong\u003E may potentially cause a similar injury if it leads to compartment syndrome of the forearm, however Volkmann\u0027s contracture is a much rarer complication of radial fractures compared to humeral fractures. Additionally, it is worth noting that vascular damage at the level of the distal radius would not cause ischaemia of the forearm flexors, as the vascular supply to these originates much more proximally.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Volkmann\u0027s ischaemic contractures most commonly result from a displaced supracondylar fracture.","Early recognition and management of compartment syndrome are crucial to prevent Volkmann\u0027s contracture."],"references":["Mirza TM, Shrestha AB. Volkmann Contracture. [Updated 2021 Apr 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557754/","Pettitt DA, McArthur P. Clinical review: Volkmann\u0027s ischaemic contracture. Eur J Trauma Emerg Surg. 2012 Apr;38(2):129-37. doi: 10.1007/s00068-011-0079-4. Epub 2011 Feb 22. PMID: 26815829. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26815829/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68065"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1897"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1943"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1943"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6dd796b8-731e-4367-b5a6-bdd72053913b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6dd796b8-731e-4367-b5a6-bdd72053913b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":351}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68065"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T21:26:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T21:27:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1897"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83005"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2